mts.s:
A Communication Covenant is an agreement every member of a team makes about communicating: 
	·  	promising to communicate regularly (even when the news is bad),
	·  	promising to answer your email how many times a day,
	·  	agreeing that you will be using Google Docs for file management,
	·  	specifying when and where your meetings are (1-2 times a week),
	·  	promising to notify team mates if you can’t make a meeting,
	·  	agreeing to reasonable punishments if a team mate is late or misses without notifying everyone,
	·  	promising to volunteer to do things and to do them well and on time.

Make sure to speak up and ensure you have given your input. Spread any and all ideas among the group through Email, text, phone calls, face to face, facebook, and any other forms that the other members may use. Make sure you are comfortable with decisions made at beginning, not after work has started. In the event of conflicting ideas, a vote will be taken by all to decide what action to take.

ASSIGNMENT #1:  Communication Covenant 
by Above Average Joes

Team Members: Joseph Chang, Van Erick Custodio, Tuan Vo, Brian Wance

Executive Summary: 
The purpose of this Communication Covenant is to establish a communication protocol to facilitate good team dynamics. This living document will open to future change with any and all changes to be approved by all.

Communication Protocol: 
Make sure to speak up and ensure you have given your input. Spread any and all ideas among the group through Email, text, phone calls, face to face, facebook, and any other forms that the other members may use (proper use of these methods described below). Make sure you are comfortable with decisions made at beginning, not after work has started. In the event of conflicting ideas, an open discussion weighing the conflicting ideas will be conducted. As a last resort and if meeting time constraints require moving on, a vote will be taken by all to decide what action to take. Please note, if your ideas were not voted in by your team, DO NOT take it personal. 

It is also important to communicate:
Emergencies
Sudden schedule conflicts
Misunderstanding of roles/duties
Misunderstanding of assignment requirements
Completion/Incompletion of an assigned individual task
Trouble performing an assigned individual task

These types of communication (though not limited to these) will be expected of each member.

Email:
When sending email add [INF 151] to the subject line so that it makes it easier for other team members to spot in their inbox.

Check your email at least twice a day, at midday and at early evening. This will give you ample time to respond and take action before it is too late. It also gives other team members to respond to your reply.

When an email is sent to the team, make sure to respond in a timely manner. This reply can be to simply inform that the message was received and the action will be taken later. This way, all team members know that the message was received.


Google Docs:
All documents whether drafts or final will be created and edited in Google Docs. All team members are responsible for contributing to all documents.

Skype:
In the event that certain decisions could not be made during a face-to-face meeting with the team, a Skype meeting will be scheduled to handle that and any unresolved business from the meeting.

Phone:
Phone numbers will be exchanged and team members can call each other to communicate. Please respect other team member’s time and only call within reasonable hours.

Texting:
Sending text messages are allowable as mode of communication when needing to send short urgent messages to the team (e.g. confirming meeting time). Group texts can be sent within reason; avoid spamming other team members who are not the primary recipients of the text message.

Meetings: In accordance to the will of the team, there has been a consensus and establishment of a repeating and consistent meeting time and place for the purpose of convening ideas and expressing our differing opinions should they arise. The main meeting time is set at 10am-11am on Fridays at Humanities Hall (at the time of this writing a second meeting is yet to be scheduled). To supplement our recurring weekly meeting schedule, we have also agreed to set aside small amounts of time before class sessions throughout the week in order to have a fluid and agile collaborative environment. The times for these face-to-face “mini” meetings are set for 12:30pm-1pm on Mondays and Wednesdays.

If a team member will miss or be late for a meeting, communication must be sent to the other team members prior.

Being late to meetings without notice will result in a consequence. The tardy team member must bring Slim Jims for Brian and donuts for the rest of the members, to the next meeting. 

Communication Conduct Expectations: Treat each other as expected in a professional work environment. Be kind, be courteous, and be civil (in both discourse and manner). Criticism is allowed, but must be constructive. Each team member must commit to contribute to all activities as best they can. If a team member lacks knowledge or skills in a particular area, that person must communicate to the team so that proper action can be taken either for another team member to assist or teach that team member. Above all, teamwork and cooperation is expected.
